Pastime &
The Present
-----------

On Thursday afternoon, just as we were putting the finishing touches on Joh=
n
Ourand=E2=80=99s characteristically excellent private email, The Varsity ( =
https://puck.news/newsletters/the-varsity/?utm_campaign=3DThe+Backstory+-+S=
UBSCRIBERS+%282%2F22%2F25%29&utm_content=3DThe+Backstory+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282=
%2F22%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=
=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ), a seismic and yet entirely predictable piece of ne=
ws came over the transom: ESPN and Major League Baseball, it was reported, =
had decided to end their multidecade relationship at the culmination of thi=
s upcoming season. Indeed, on some level, this was hardly a surprise. ESPN=
=E2=80=99s top executives have been gesturing for
months that they want to exercise an out in their contract and renegotiate =
their $570 million per year deal. After all, MLB=E2=80=99s recent secondary=
 deals with Apple TV+ and Roku, worth about a combined $100 million per yea=
r, seemed to suggest that ESPN had overpaid and there was room to negotiate=
 downward.

=C2=A0

And yet the tenor of the divorce was a total shocker. After decades of part=
nership between the league and
the network, MLB commissioner Rob Manfred wrote to his franchise owners tha=
t =E2=80=9Cwe do not think it=E2=80=99s beneficial for us to accept a small=
er deal to remain on a shrinking platform=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94fighting words, =
especially in the clubby, towel-slapping culture of sports media. I had lon=
g expected that ESPN and MLB might find some sort of goldilocks solution=E2=
=80=94perhaps a smaller tranche of games and highlights for a lower price=
=E2=80=94that would allow each side to claim victory. Alas, this 35-year ma=
rriage
now seemed over.

=C2=A0

On a personal level, I admit, I was slightly crestfallen over the news. ESP=
N=E2=80=99s Sunday Night Baseball has been a hallmark of my life since adol=
escence, and it will be sad to see its demise. Furthermore, amid an era in =
which the NFL and NBA have achieved unprecedented sports rights packages, b=
aseball remains on uncertain footing. Its vast schedule and the collapse of=
 the regional
sports network business have provided unique obstacles. A sport that came o=
f age during the radio era appears to have a less obvious foothold in the s=
treaming age.

=C2=A0

John covered the news as it broke on Thursday, and he=E2=80=99ll have the l=
atest beats in The Varsity on Monday. Meanwhile, Dylan Byers captured the e=
thos of the ESPN negotiations in his latest excellent dispatch,
No Joy in Manfred=E2=80=99s Mudville ( https://puck.news/why-the-espn-mlb-d=
eal-blew-up/?utm_campaign=3DThe+Backstory+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F22%2F25%29&u=
tm_content=3DThe+Backstory+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F22%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Dema=
il_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ). Like al=
l the best Puck stories, this tale captures the conflict between an institu=
tion=E2=80=99s past and present=E2=80=94a leitmotif here this week. McMahon=
 on Fire & Politico=E2=80=99s Prince Valiant ( https://puck.news/cbs-news-h=
ead-wendy-mcmahons-seat-is-very-hot/?utm_campaign=3DThe+Backstory+-+SUBSCRI=
BERS+%282%2F22%2F25%29&utm_content=3DThe+Backstory+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F22%=
2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60=
617da42abd12a ), Dylan=E2=80=99s previous piece,
articulated the dilemmas of CBS and Politico as they wade through uncertain=
 waters. Similarly, in Even Republicans Have DOGE Anxiety Attacks ( https:/=
/puck.news/doge-is-giving-the-gop-heartburn-too-at-0-cost-to-taxpayers/?utm=
_campaign=3DThe+Backstory+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F22%2F25%29&utm_content=3DThe=
+Backstory+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F22%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_so=
urce=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ), Leigh Ann Caldwell port=
rayed a party at its latest crossroads. And yet, perhaps no piece captured =
the tension more poignantly than Lauren Sherman=E2=80=99s
Notes From the Saks Apocalypse ( https://puck.news/saks-well-pay-you-in-90-=
not-30-days-vendors-grr-argh/?utm_campaign=3DThe+Backstory+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2=
82%2F22%2F25%29&utm_content=3DThe+Backstory+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F22%2F25%29=
&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42=
abd12a )=E2=80=94a meditation on the future of multibrand retail as demonst=
rated by Saks Global, a roll-up of ole department stores Saks, Neiman Marcu=
s, and Bergdorf Goodman.

=C2=A0

But if you have time to read only one piece, I=E2=80=99d turn your attentio=
n to Matt
Belloni=E2=80=99s latest masterstroke, Why the Broccolis Gave Up Bond ( htt=
ps://puck.news/what-is-amazon-going-to-do-with-james-bond/?utm_campaign=3DT=
he+Backstory+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F22%2F25%29&utm_content=3DThe+Backstory+-+=
SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F22%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustom=
er.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ), which focuses on how the stewards of=
 the 007 franchise capitulated to Amazon=E2=80=99s will and endless balance=
 sheet. It=E2=80=99s a story about technological transformation=E2=80=94bot=
h what=E2=80=99s gained, and what=E2=80=99s lost along the way. And in that=
 regard, it=E2=80=99s the story of our time, and precisely what you should =
expect
from Puck.

